HEADWORD: Archimandrite
<hw>Ar`chi*man"drite</hw> <pr>(⟦aum⟧r`k⟦icr⟧m⟦acr⟧n"dr⟦imac⟧t)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>archimandrita</ets>, LGr.
<grk>'archimandri`ths</grk>; pref. <grk>'archi</grk> (E.
<ets>arch-</ets>) + <grk>ma`ndra</grk> an inclosed space, esp. for
cattle, a fold, a monastery.]</ety> <fld>(Gr. Church)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>A chief of a monastery, corresponding to <xex>abbot</xex> in the
Roman Catholic church.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A superintendent of
several monasteries, corresponding to <xex>superior abbot</xex>, or
<xex>father provincial</xex>, in the Roman Catholic church.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Archimedean</ent>⟦br⟧
